She turned to a blank page and wrote the date. Below, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you rereading memories?" Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's only a few days away now."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The King of Ice never let Kari out, because she was "a mistake" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in the family, which was otherwise composed solely of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had spoken of her non-binary identity, it was as if the world had also changed. She had been given tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
Iel had to stay in service to the princess as well, but it wasn't a big deal, since it gave her a friend.
"Is it almost your birthday, I think?" Ivory asked, remembering that the princess's birthday was coming up in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad gleam in her pale blue eyes.
"Would you like to celebrate it?" As she asked the question, iel remembered what she had answered the last time.
No, Kari touched her foot. Ivory knew it was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she had been confined to her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but iel remembered the outrage of the servants and the townspeople. Iel had heard it said that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but that she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Okay... what do you want to do?" iel asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed Ivory a piece of paper. But when iel glanced at it...
Painting canvas 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Would you like me to find these things for you?" Ivory said, turning toward the silent princess who was tapping frantically, shaking her braids back and forth. "Yes?" Iel giggled slightly at seeing the usually reserved princess become so passionate about something. It was the first time she had asked for something unrelated to books and that wasn't in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" Ivory offered, standing up and making her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and immersed herself again in her memories, wrapping herself once more in her thick braid.
Iel left the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that weren't within her realm, like painting.
Iel turned back through the corridors, trying not to listen to the whispers of the servants.
"I heard she was possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes to that room."
"I heard she eats children in this room."
"Does she look like a man, don't you think?"
Iel covered her ears because trying to ignore it wasn't working. Iel headed toward the royal painter's chamber, which was located in the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately carved as Kari's. It bore a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, who according to legend had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved the story.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. There were paint stains everywhere, pencils and papers scattered around the room, easels covering every last centimeter of the wall. Surprisingly, Iel saw none of this. The room was clean and there was a red velvet background with a stool just in front. On the stool stood Prince Aquilo, who was being painted.
"Ah, hello, Ivory! Are you here to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" asked Aquilo, giving Ivory a wink.
"Pardon, little prince," replied Iel, partially ignoring him in order to search for the items her silent friend desired. "I'm just here to retrieve supplies."
"Ah, the little girl is going to leave very soon?" asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
" Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies from her list and placed them in a box that Iel had found. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought about it, however. "Oh my darling, you know it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up," he muttered.
"I have to go," said Iel, suddenly feeling uneasy because of the prince's words, which reminded her of all the bad things people had said about her gender identity. I really want to distance myself from him.
"Are you already leaving?" The Prince appeared immediately at the door, ignoring the painter royal's complaints.
"that's not the behavior of a future king!" Iel reprimanded him.
"Nobody will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he cares about his life." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned toward Ivory. "What do you say to a date?" Iel shivered. Certainly, Iel had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, let alone an heir to the throne.
"Doesn't the word 'no' mean anything to you?" Iel shouted, shoving the prince aside to make her way through.
"Huh no," replied Aquilo with a smile. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want to go on a date with me instead of others? You must have a hundred suitors at least?"
He interrupted her, still smiling: "Exactly 500." He threw back his hair, letting it fly in the cold air.
"So, why me instead of someone else? I'm the palace's threat." Iel wrapped her arms around her body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
